<section class="section" id="how-it-works">
  <h2>How the herd works</h2>
  <p>
    A directive becomes a mission; the brain decomposes it into a
    dependency-ordered task queue; the agents pull ready tasks and execute
    them; their structured findings feed a two-tier re-planner; the mission
    converges when the client accepts.
  </p>
  <pre class="flow">CLIENT (you, or a modeled product-owner agent)
  │ directive ↓                 ↑ accept / feedback → next sprint
  ▼                             │
LEAD ── research → design → build-core → build → test ∥ secops ∥ perf → integrate → docs → retro
(orchestrates,        the dev team (one role per phase)
 re-plans, reworks)          SCRUM (standups · stall call-outs · nudges)
  └── findings → reflex fix+verify  ∥  lead supersede / re-architect → converge</pre>

  <div class="tech-grid">
    <div class="tech">
      <h3>Cross-model review, decorrelated by construction</h3>
      <p>
        Most agent-swarm frameworks run one LLM in every role — parallelism
        with <em>correlated</em> blind spots, because the "reviewer" shares
        the builder's failure modes when it's the same model underneath.
        Corral lets each role run a genuinely different model — a Claude
        builder, a Gemini reviewer, a local model for the cheap passes — all
        coordinating through one brain, so review becomes adversarial and
        decorrelated by construction, not by hoping the temperature setting
        helps. Mix cheap local agents with frontier ones in the same mission,
        and pay for it however you already do — a metered API key <em>or</em> a
        subscription CLI like Codex or Claude Max. Bring anything
        OpenAI-compatible or a local model: no vendor lock-in.
      </p>
      <a href="/docs/concepts/multi-model-herds/">Multi-model herds →</a>
    </div>
    <div class="tech">
      <h3>The verify gate — a quality floor, not a vibe</h3>
      <p>
        A task isn't "done" because an agent says so. The verification gate
        refuses completion until a real command — <code>go test</code>,
        <code>pytest</code>, <code>npm test</code>, <code>cargo test</code>,
        anything — is on record with a passing exit code. A failing build
        becomes a finding, not an assumption.
      </p>
      <a href="/docs/concepts/queue-and-verify/">The task queue + verify gate →</a>
    </div>
    <div class="tech">
      <h3>Two-tier re-planning</h3>
      <p>
        Findings don't just pile up in a backlog. High-severity findings
        trigger a <strong>reflex tier</strong> that deterministically spawns
        fix-and-reverify tasks — no LLM in the loop, fast and predictable.
        Judgment calls — superseding stale work, reopening something thought
        done, re-architecting a bad approach — go to an <strong>LLM lead
        tier</strong>, with full task lineage so nothing disappears silently.
        Convergence is bounded: caps and loop-until-dry keep a stuck mission
        from re-planning forever.
      </p>
      <a href="/docs/concepts/mission-lifecycle/">Mission lifecycle →</a>
    </div>
    <div class="tech">
      <h3>Path claims and leases — the coordination substrate</h3>
      <p>
        A dozen agents working the same repo need a way to not step on each
        other. The coordination layer is transactional SQLite: atomic
        exclusive claims on paths and branches, time-boxed with a TTL, a
        presence/lease reaper that reclaims work from an agent that went
        quiet, and a durable completed-work log. No file gets two writers; no
        claim outlives its holder.
      </p>
      <a href="/docs/concepts/claims-and-leases/">Claims &amp; leases →</a>
    </div>
    <div class="tech">
      <h3>Jail → repo — the only way code leaves</h3>
      <p>
        Every agent's shell commands run inside a <code>bwrap</code> jail: no
        network by default, workspace-confined, a secret-free environment —
        the git/forge token lives only in the brain, never handed to an
        agent. The only egress is a pull request the brain opens and watches;
        a <code>CHANGES_REQUESTED</code> review reopens rework automatically.
        Because every consequential action funnels through the brain, it's
        also the forensic record — attributed to a verified principal, and
        the subject of the record doesn't control the ledger.
      </p>
      <a href="/docs/concepts/trust-and-security/">Trust &amp; security →</a>
    </div>
    <div class="tech">
      <h3>And it learns</h3>
      <p>
        Recurring findings don't just get fixed once — they get swept into
        skill proposals a human approves, so every later mission starts
        already warned. See how the learning loop works below.
      </p>
      <a href="#learning-loop">The learning loop ↓</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

